[
    {
        "content": "<p>In <a class=\"stream-topic\" data-stream-id=\"217875\" href=\"/#narrow/channel/217875-Is-there-code-for-X.3F/topic/diagonalizable.20linear.20maps/with/539176450\">#Is there code for X? &gt; diagonalizable linear maps</a>  <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"816344\">@Aaron Liu</span> and I stumbled upon a very strange ring which is Z/6Z, and the equally strange (Z/6Z)[X], and now I have a conjecture:</p>\n<p><strong>Conjecture</strong>: there are no irreducible elements in (Z/6Z)[X]</p>\n<p>is this true?</p>",
        "id": 539176579,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1757718891
    },
    {
        "content": "<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">open</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Polynomial</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">theorem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">not_irreducible_of_polynomial_zmod_6</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">ZMod</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">6</span><span class=\"o\">)[</span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">])</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">¬</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Irreducible</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"gr\">sorry</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 539176709,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1757718977
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This ring is presumably just a product of the rings <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mn>2</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Z/2[X]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span><span class=\"mord\">/2</span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mn>3</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Z/3[X]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span><span class=\"mord\">/3</span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> so one could ask the more general question about a product of two PIDs. Is (irreducible,1) irreducible in such a thing? Sounds to me like it might be, so maybe I'm suggesting <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">1+2X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7278em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> as a counterexample?</p>",
        "id": 539179431,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1757720924
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>that makes sense, i think that works</p>",
        "id": 539179597,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1757721027
    },
    {
        "content": "<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Text only\"><pre><span></span><code>Tactic `decide` proved that the proposition\n  ∀ (a b c d : ZMod 6), a * c = 0 → b * d = 1 → a * d + b * c = 2 → False\nis false\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 539180069,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1757721311
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>well but the factors could be quadratic</p>",
        "id": 539180118,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1757721339
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>e.g. (2x+3)(3x+2) = x</p>",
        "id": 539180139,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1757721351
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>no that's not what I mean</p>",
        "id": 539180174,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1757721377
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>also irreducible doesn't mean no factorisation exists, it means that if it factorises as ab then a or b must be unit</p>",
        "id": 539180198,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1757721396
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>oh I guess I forgot to clean out the units</p>",
        "id": 539180217,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1757721409
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>ok the factors can't both be linear</p>",
